 television series]]\n[[Category:South Korean romance television series]]\n[[Category:Television series set in universities and colleges]]\n[[Category:Sequel television series]]\n", "name_user": "Seokgjin", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eProduction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hello,_My_Twenties!_2"}
{"title_page": "Henry Lee Moore", "text_new": "{{short description|American murderer and suspected serial killer}}\n{{Infobox serial killer\n| name        = Henry Lee Moore\n| image       = File:Henry_Moore.gif\n| image_size  = \n| caption     = Photo of Moore from a newspaper excerpt\n| alt         = \n| birth_name  = \n| alias       = L. Smith<br>Hellum\n| birth_date  = 1874\n| birth_place = [[Boone County, Missouri]], United States\n| death_place = After 1956\n| conviction  = [[Murder]]\n| sentence    = [[Life imprisonment]]; later commuted and released in 1949\n| victims     = 2\u201325\n| beginyear   = 1911\n| endyear     = 1912\n| country     = United States\n| states      = [[Missouri]], [[Illinois]], [[Iowa]], [[Colorado]], [[Kansas]]\n| apprehended = \n| imprisoned  = \n}}\n'''Henry Lee Moore''' (was born in 1874 in [[Boone County, Missouri]], date of death unknown) was an American [[forger]], murderer and suspected [[serial killer]] who was convicted of killing his mother and grandmother with an axe in their home.<ref name=SK>{{Citeweb|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn84020630/1913-05-08/ed-1/seq-1/#date1=1912&sort=date&rows=20&words=Henry+Lee+Moore&searchType=basic&sequence=0&index=8&state=&date2=1913&proxtext=Henry+Lee+Moore&y=0&x=0&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=2|title=Moore Believed To Have Outclassed Bluebeard Or Mrs. Guinnes As Murderer|newspaper=[[The Santa Fe New Mexican]] |date=8 May 1913}}</ref> While in prison, it was alleged by a [[United States Department of Justice|Justice Department]] agent named W. M. McClaughry that Moore was possibly responsible for a string of unsolved axe murders in several states, among them being the [[Villisca axe murders|Villisca axe Murders]].<ref name=SK/>\n\n==Early life and first imprisonment==\nBorn and raised in Boone County, Moore lived on the outskirts of [[Columbia, Missouri|Columbia]] with his mother and grandmother, but worked as a blacksmith's helper at various car shops in [[Moberly, Missouri|Moberly]], along the [[Wabash Railroad]].<ref name=dual>{{Citeweb|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn92053934/1912-12-19/ed-1/seq-1/#date1=1912&sort=date&rows=20&words=Henry+Lee+Moore&searchType=basic&sequence=0&index=2&state=&date2=1913&proxtext=Henry+Lee+Moore&y=0&x=0&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=1|title=Son Held For Dual Murder|newspaper=[[The Dispatch / The Rock Island Argus|The Rock Island Argus]]|date=19 December 1912}}</ref> Although described as a friendly-looking man, he had the morbid habit of visiting various morgues in [[St. Louis]] with the purpose of looking at the bodies. Not only that, he also collected newspaper scraps from infamous criminal cases, including that of Dr. [[Hawley Harvey Crippen]].<ref name=eve>{{Citeweb|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn89066313/1913-03-07/ed-1/seq-3/#date1=1912&sort=date&rows=20&words=Henry+Lee+Moore&searchType=basic&sequence=0&index=13&state=&date2=1913&proxtext=Henry+Lee+Moore&y=0&x=0&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=1|title=On Eve Of His Trial Moore Is Confident|newspaper=University Missourian |date=7 March 1913}}</ref><ref name=charge>{{Citeweb|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn89067274/1913-03-13/ed-1/seq-4/#date1=1912&sort=date&rows=20&words=Henry+Lee+Moore&searchType=basic&sequence=0&index=15&state=&date2=1913&proxtext=Henry+Lee+Moore&y=0&x=0&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=1|title=Charged With Double Murder\u2013Is On Trial|newspaper=[[The Mexico Ledger|The Mexico Weekly Ledger]] |date=13 March 1913}}</ref>\n\nMoore communicated with various women through letters,<ref name=girl>{{Citeweb|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82016014/1912-12-27/ed-1/seq-2/#date1=1912&sort=date&rows=20&words=Henry+Lee+Moore&searchType=basic&sequence=0&index=7&state=&date2=1913&proxtext=Henry+Lee+Moore&y=0&x=0&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=1|title=Girl in Axe Case|newspaper=The Topeka State Journal |date=27 December 1912}}</ref> and in May 1910, he was arrested in [[Wichita, Kansas]] for forgery. He was convicted and sentenced to a year of imprisonment in the [[Hutchinson Correctional Facility|Hutchinson Reformatory]],<ref name=ready>{{Citeweb|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn89066313/1913-03-09/ed-1/seq-3/#date1=1912&sort=date&rows=20&words=Henry+Lee+Moore&searchType=basic&sequence=0&index=14&state=&date2=1913&proxtext=Henry+Lee+Moore&y=0&x=0&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=1|title=State Is Ready For Moore Trial|newspaper=University Missourian |date=9 March 1913}}</ref> receiving his parole in May 1911.<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82016014/1913-05-08/ed-1/seq-7/#date1=1912&sort=date&rows=20&words=Henry+Lee+Moore&searchType=basic&sequence=0&index=4&state=&date2=1913&proxtext=Henry+Lee+Moore&y=0&x=0&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=2|title=Moore's Record|newspaper=[[The Topeka Capital-Journal|The Topeka State Journal]] |date=8 May 1913}}</ref>\n\n==Double murders==\nSometime after his release, Moore began corresponding with a 16-year-old Columbia girl named Queenie Nichols, eventually professing his love for her.<ref name=girl/> However, Nichols rejected him because he had no home of his own.<ref name=charge/> In response to this, he wrote a letter to her that soon his mother's home would be his, along with all the money in there.<ref name=girl/>\n\nA day before the murder, Moore travelled by train to Columbia and registered at the Central Hotel under the alias of L. Smith.<ref name=girl/><ref name=charge/> On the night of December 17, 1912, he snuck into the house carrying a rusty axe with a broken handle which was normally used for handling coal. He crept up behind his 63-year-old mother Georgia, who was sitting in a chair and rubbing herself with an ointment for her joints, and began hitting her on the neck and head.<ref name=dual/>\n\nAfter killing her, Henry moved on to the bedroom, where his 82-year-old grandmother Mary Wilson was sleeping. Using this as an advantage, he struck her with the axe on the neck and head, killing Wilson before she could make a move to defend herself.<ref name=dual/> Shortly thereafter Henry left the house, disposing of the axe in a nearby ditch.<ref name=charge/> He then returned to his hotel room to clean off the blood, but in his haste left a lot of it on the bedsheets, his clothes and some on his arms.<ref name=girl/>\n\nThe following day, he pretended to have just arrived and upon \"discovering\" the bodies, he called the neighbors. Police came to the scene, but after investigating Henry's whereabouts he was quickly arrested, as it was quickly revealed that he had stayed in the hotel and blood was found on his clothing and bed sheets for which no explanation was given.<ref name=girl/> Authorities also found an [[insurance policy]] in Moore's pocket, but it turned out that it had been on Henry life, payable to his mother.<ref name=dual/>\n\n==Trial, sentence and later life==\nWhile incarcerated, Moore refused to comment on the murders, but talked freely about his character, his poetry and his innocence.<ref name=eve/> According to him, he had just arrived in town from Moberly to celebrate [[Christmas]],<ref name=dual/> and simply happened upon the grisly crime scene. He also denied all the claims made by the newspapers about his nighttime morgue visits, proudly stating that nobody in his family had even been convicted of a crime and that this was his first time in prison.<ref name=eve/>\n\nUpon further investigation, Prosecuting Attorney E. C. Anderson quickly debunked Moore's explanations, stating that there were witnesses and enough circumstantial evidence to connect him to the killings. He also noted that the accused's claim of being a student at the [[Kansas State University College of Agriculture|Kansas State Agricultural College]] was simply untrue, and concerning his prison sentence, Anderson said that Moore was most likely a drug addict.<ref name=ready/> Despite all of his protestation of innocence, Henry Lee Moore was found guilty of the double murder on March 14, after a four-day trial with 80 jurors present,<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn89066313/1913-01-15/ed-1/seq-1/#date1=1912&sort=date&rows=20&words=Henry+Lee+Moore&searchType=basic&sequence=0&index=9&state=&date2=1913&proxtext=Henry+Lee+Moore&y=0&x=0&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=1|title=Moore's Trial Set|newspaper=[[University Missourian]] |date=15 January 1913}}</ref> with the jury giving him a sentence of [[life imprisonment]].<ref name=guilty>{{Citeweb|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82016014/1913-03-14/ed-1/seq-1/#date1=1912&sort=date&rows=20&words=Henry+Lee+Moore&searchType=basic&sequence=0&index=17&state=&date2=1913&proxtext=Henry+Lee+Moore&y=0&x=0&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=1|title=Moore Found Guilty|newspaper=The Topeka State Journal |date=14 March 1913}}</ref> His attorney tried to appeal to the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]], but his request was denied.<ref name=guilty/>\n\nMoore's sentenced was commuted on July 30, 1956, and he was released. The then-82-year-old was last recorded as living at a [[Salvation Army]] Center in St. Louis, and after that, no further information about him is available.\n\n==Serial killer?==\nAfter some time, Moore's fingerprints and prison record were sent in for examination by W. M. McClaughry, an investigator in the Villisca axe murders, to J. H. Livingston, a fingerprinting expert in [[Jefferson City, Missouri|Jefferson City]].<ref name=tell>{{Citeweb|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85050913/1913-05-27/ed-1/seq-6/#date1=1912&sort=date&rows=20&words=Henry+Lee+Moore&searchType=basic&sequence=0&index=10&state=&date2=1913&proxtext=Henry+Lee+Moore&y=0&x=0&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=4|title=Detective M'Claughry Tells Ax Crime Theory|newspaper=Webster City Freeman |date=27 May 1913}}</ref> Livingston suggested that the prisoner could have something to do with the string of axe murders, which, coupled with the coincidental timing that Moore had just been released at the start of the spree, led McClaughry to propose this theory.<ref name=SK/><ref name=tell/> According to it, Moore was possibly responsible for these murders:<ref name=SK/>\n* Burnham-Wayne Murders (September 17, 1911, in [[Colorado Springs, Colorado]]): Henry F. Wayne, his wife and child, along with the visiting Mrs. Burnham and her two children, were killed at the Waynes' home. Arthur Burnham, the husband of one of the victims, was arrested on suspicion but later released due to lack of evidence. He later died from [[tuberculosis]], still protesting his innocence.\n* Dawson Murders (October 1911, in [[Monmouth, Illinois]]): M. E. Dawson, along with his wife and daughter, were killed with an axe.\n* Showman Murders (October 1911, in [[Ellsworth, Kansas]]): William Showman, along with his wife and three children, were also killed with an axe.\n* Hudson Murders (June 1912, in [[Paola, Kansas]]): Roland Hudson and his wife were killed with an axe.\n* [[Villisca axe murders]] (June 10\u201311, 1912 in [[Villisca, Iowa]]): the Moore Family (no relation to Henry Lee Moore), as well as two visiting girls named Ina Mae and Lena Stillinger, were brutally killed at the Moores' home.\n\nMcClaughry's theory was overblown by the contemporary media, who claimed that he was stating it as fact and not speculation.<ref name=tell/> An inquest was even started by Police Chief Burno, of Colorado Springs, into the Burnham-Wayne murders, as a man resembling Moore was seen in the city following the grisly killings, but had quickly left and was never seen again.<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn90051521/1913-05-09/ed-1/seq-1/#date1=1912&sort=date&rows=20&words=Henry+Lee+Moore&searchType=basic&sequence=0&index=4&state=&date2=1913&proxtext=Henry+Lee+Moore&y=0&x=0&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=3|title=Axeman Murder Probe Revived At The Springs|newspaper=The Chronicle News |date=9 May 1913}}</ref> However, this was later discredited by M. F. Amrine, Superintendent of the Kansas State Reformatory, who reported that Moore was corresponding with him at the time of the murders, and that Henry was at home in Columbia.<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn99021999/1913-05-27/ed-1/seq-2/#date1=1912&sort=date&rows=20&words=Henry+Lee+Moore&searchType=basic&sequence=0&index=11&state=&date2=1913&proxtext=Henry+Lee+Moore&y=0&x=0&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=4|title=Alibi Established For Alleged Axeman|newspaper=[[Omaha Daily Bee]] |date=27 May 1913}}</ref>\n\nA similar inquest was also initiated by Chief Chargeois, for a 1911 axe murder that took place in [[Lafayette, Louisiana]]. Although [[Clementine Barnabet]] and one of her followers were suspected of that crime, the man had already been imprisoned at the time of the killings. The result from the investigation is currently unknown, but it is presumed that it was called off.<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88064402/1913-05-23/ed-1/seq-2/#date1=1912&sort=date&rows=20&words=Henry+Lee+Moore&searchType=basic&sequence=0&index=6&state=&date2=1913&proxtext=Henry+Lee+Moore&y=0&x=0&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=4|title=Working On Axe Murders|newspaper=The Rice Belt Journal |date=23 May 1913}}</ref>\n\nIn regard to the Villisca murders, few of the residents believed the theory.<ref name=calm>{{Citeweb|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85050913/1913-05-13/ed-1/seq-8/#date1=1912&sort=date&rows=20&words=Henry+Lee+Moore&searchType=basic&sequence=0&index=6&state=&date2=1913&proxtext=Henry+Lee+Moore&y=0&x=0&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=3|title=Theory of Crime Calmly Received|newspaper=Webster City Freeman |date=13 May 1913}}</ref> However, according to Joseph Stillinger, father of the killed Lena, claimed that Moore very much resembled a man that once worked for him.<ref name=clew>{{Citeweb|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn90061371/1913-05-14/ed-1/seq-2/#date1=1912&sort=date&rows=20&words=Henry+Lee+Moore&searchType=basic&sequence=0&index=11&state=&date2=1913&proxtext=Henry+Lee+Moore&y=0&x=0&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=3|title=Trace Clew to Ax Murder|newspaper=Potosi Journal |date=14 May 1913}}</ref> That man, who had given his name as \"Hellum\", was hired in April 1912, and worked for only a week before disappearing.<ref name=calm/> Stillinger and an officer later went on to confront Moore in prison, but, most likely, the mysterious man was not Henry Lee Moore.<ref name=clew/>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of serial killers in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://murderpedia.org/male.M/m/moore-henry-lee.htm Murderpedia Article]\n* [https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/182234612/henry-lee-moore FindAGrave Memorial]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lee Moore, Henry}}\n[[Category:1874 births]]\n[[Category:Date of death unknown]]\n[[Category:20th-century criminals]]\n[[Category:Male serial killers]]\n[[Category:American serial killers]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by Missouri]]\n[[Category:People convicted of forgery]]\n[[Category:Violence against women in the United States]]\n[[Category:Axe murder]]\n[[Category:Familicides]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of Missouri]]\n[[Category:People from Boone County, Missouri]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American murderer and suspected serial killer}}\n{{Infobox serial killer\n| name        = Henry Lee Moore\n| image       = File:Henry_Moore.gif\n| image_size  = \n| caption     = Photo of Moore from a newspaper excerpt\n| alt         = \n| birth_name  = \n| alias       = L. Smith<br>Hellum\n| birth_date  = 1874\n| birth_place = [[Boone County, Missouri]], United States\n| death_place = After 1956\n| conviction  = [[Murder]]\n| sentence    = [[Life imprisonment]]; later commuted and released in 1949\n| victims     = 2\u201325\n| beginyear   = 1911\n| endyear     = 1912\n| country     = United States\n| states      = [[Missouri]], [[Illinois]], [[Iowa]], [[Colorado]], [[Kansas]]\n| apprehended = \n| imprisoned  = \n}}\n'''Henry Lee Moore''' (was born in 1874 in [[Boone County, Missouri]], date of death unknown) was an American [[forger]], murderer and suspected [[serial killer]] who was convicted of killing his mother and grandmother with an axe in their home.<ref name=SK>{{Citeweb|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn84020630/1913-05-08/ed-1/seq-1/#date1=1912&sort=date&rows=20&words=Henry+Lee+Moore&searchType=basic&sequence=0&index=8&state=&date2=1913&proxtext=Henry+Lee+Moore&y=0&x=0&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=2|title=Moore Believed To Have Outclassed Bluebeard Or Mrs. Guinnes As Murderer|newspaper=[[The Santa Fe New Mexican]] |date=8 May 1913}}</ref> While in prison, it was alleged by a [[United States Department of Justice|Justice Department]] agent named W. M. McClaughry that Moore was possibly responsible for a string of unsolved axe murders in several states, among them being the [[Villisca axe murders|Villisca axe Murders]].<ref name=SK/>\n\n==Early life and first imprisonment==\nBorn and raised in Boone County, Moore lived on the outskirts of [[Columbia, Missouri|Columbia]] with his mother and grandmother, but worked as a blacksmith's helper at various car shops in [[Moberly, Missouri|Moberly]], along the [[Wabash Railroad]].<ref name=dual>{{Citeweb|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn92053934/1912-12-19/ed-1/seq-1/#date1=1912&sort=date&rows=20&words=Henry+Lee+Moore&searchType=basic&sequence=0&index=2&state=&date2=1913&proxtext=Henry+Lee+Moore&y=0&x=0&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=1|title=Son Held For Dual Murder|newspaper=[[The Dispatch / The Rock Island Argus|The Rock Island Argus]]|date=19 December 1912}}</ref> Although described as a friendly-looking man, he had the morbid habit of visiting various morgues in [[St. Louis]] with the purpose of looking at the bodies. Not only that, he also collected newspaper scraps from infamous criminal cases, including that of Dr. [[Hawley Harvey Crippen]].<ref name=eve>{{Citeweb|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn89066313/1913-03-07/ed-1/seq-3/#date1=1912&sort=date&rows=20&words=Henry+Lee+Moore&searchType=basic&sequence=0&index=13&state=&date2=1913&proxtext=Henry+Lee+Moore&y=0&x=0&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=1|title=On Eve Of His Trial Moore Is Confident|newspaper=University Missourian |date=7 March 1913}}</ref><ref name=charge>{{Citeweb|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn89067274/1913-03-13/ed-1/seq-4/#date1=1912&sort=date&rows=20&words=Henry+Lee+Moore&searchType=basic&sequence=0&index=15&state=&date2=1913&proxtext=Henry+Lee+Moore&y=0&x=0&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=1|title=Charged With Double Murder\u2013Is On Trial|newspaper=[[The Mexico Ledger|The Mexico Weekly Ledger]] |date=13 March 1913}}</ref>\n\nMoore communicated with various women through letters,<ref name=girl>{{Citeweb|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82016014/1912-12-27/ed-1/seq-2/#date1=1912&sort=date&rows=20&words=Henry+Lee+Moore&searchType=basic&sequence=0&index=7&state=&date2=1913&proxtext=Henry+Lee+Moore&y=0&x=0&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=1|title=Girl in Axe Case|newspaper=The Topeka State Journal |date=27 December 1912}}</ref> and in May 1910, he was arrested in [[Wichita, Kansas]] for forgery. He was convicted and sentenced to a year of imprisonment in the [[Hutchinson Correctional Facility|Hutchinson Reformatory]],<ref name=ready>{{Citeweb|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn89066313/1913-03-09/ed-1/seq-3/#date1=1912&sort=date&rows=20&words=Henry+Lee+Moore&searchType=basic&sequence=0&index=14&state=&date2=1913&proxtext=Henry+Lee+Moore&y=0&x=0&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=1|title=State Is Ready For Moore Trial|newspaper=University Missourian |date=9 March 1913}}</ref> receiving his parole in May 1911.<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82016014/1913-05-08/ed-1/seq-7/#date1=1912&sort=date&rows=20&words=Henry+Lee+Moore&searchType=basic&sequence=0&index=4&state=&date2=1913&proxtext=Henry+Lee+Moore&y=0&x=0&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=2|title=Moore's Record|newspaper=[[The Topeka Capital-Journal|The Topeka State Journal]] |date=8 May 1913}}</ref>\n\n==Double murders==\nSometime after his release, Moore began corresponding with a 16-year-old Columbia girl named Queenie Nichols, eventually professing his love for her.<ref name=girl/> However, Nichols rejected him because he had no home of his own.<ref name=charge/> In response to this, he wrote a letter to her that soon his mother's home would be his, along with all the money in there.<ref name=girl/>\n\nA day before the murder, Moore travelled by train to Columbia and registered at the Central Hotel under the alias of L. Smith.<ref name=girl/><ref name=charge/> On the night of December 17, 1912, he snuck into the house carrying a rusty axe with a broken handle which was normally used for handling coal. He crept up behind his 63-year-old mother Georgia, who was sitting in a chair and rubbing herself with an ointment for her joints, and began hitting her on the neck and head.<ref name=dual/>\n\nAfter killing her, Henry moved on to the bedroom, where his 82-year-old grandmother Mary Wilson was sleeping. Using this as an advantage, he struck her with the axe on the neck and head, killing Wilson before she could make a move to defend herself.<ref name=dual/> Shortly thereafter Henry left the house, disposing of the axe in a nearby ditch.<ref name=charge/> He then returned to his hotel room to clean off the blood, but in his haste left a lot of it on the bedsheets, his clothes and some on his arms.<ref name=girl/>\n\nThe following day, he pretended to have just arrived and upon \"discovering\" the bodies, he called the neighbors. Police came to the scene, but after investigating Henry's whereabouts he was quickly arrested, as it was quicky revealed that he had stayed in the hotel and blood was found on his clothing and bed sheets for which no explanation was given.<ref name=girl/> Authorities also found an [[insurance policy]] in Moore's pocket, but it turned out that it had been on Henry life, payable to his mother.<ref name=dual/>\n\n==Trial, sentence and later life==\nWhile incarcerated, Moore refused to comment on the murders, but talked freely about his character, his poetry and his innocence.<ref name=eve/> According to him, he had just arrived in town from Moberly to celebrate [[Christmas]],<ref name=dual/> and simply happened upon the grisly crime scene. He also denied all the claims made by the newspapers about his nighttime morgue visits, proudly stating that nobody in his family had even been convicted of a crime and that this was his first time in prison.<ref name=eve/>\n\nUpon further investigation, Prosecuting Attorney E. C. Anderson quickly debunked Moore's explanations, stating that there were witnesses and enough circumstantial evidence to connect him to the killings. He also noted that the accused's claim of being a student at the [[Kansas State University College of Agriculture|Kansas State Agricultural College]] was simply untrue, and concerning his prison sentence, Anderson said that Moore was most likely a drug addict.<ref name=ready/> Despite all of his protestation of innocence, Henry Lee Moore was found guilty of the double murder on March 14, after a four-day trial with 80 jurors present,<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn89066313/1913-01-15/ed-1/seq-1/#date1=1912&sort=date&rows=20&words=Henry+Lee+Moore&searchType=basic&sequence=0&index=9&state=&date2=1913&proxtext=Henry+Lee+Moore&y=0&x=0&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=1|title=Moore's Trial Set|newspaper=[[University Missourian]] |date=15 January 1913}}</ref> with the jury giving him a sentence of [[life imprisonment]].<ref name=guilty>{{Citeweb|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82016014/1913-03-14/ed-1/seq-1/#date1=1912&sort=date&rows=20&words=Henry+Lee+Moore&searchType=basic&sequence=0&index=17&state=&date2=1913&proxtext=Henry+Lee+Moore&y=0&x=0&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=1|title=Moore Found Guilty|newspaper=The Topeka State Journal |date=14 March 1913}}</ref> His attorney tried to appeal to the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]], but his request was denied.<ref name=guilty/>\n\nMoore's sentenced was commuted on July 30, 1956, and he was released. The then-82-year-old was last recorded as living at a [[Salvation Army]] Center in St. Louis, and after that, no further information about him is available.\n\n==Serial killer?==\nAfter some time, Moore's fingerprints and prison record were sent in for examination by W. M. McClaughry, an investigator in the Villisca axe murders, to J. H. Livingston, a fingerprinting expert in [[Jefferson City, Missouri|Jefferson City]].<ref name=tell>{{Citeweb|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85050913/1913-05-27/ed-1/seq-6/#date1=1912&sort=date&rows=20&words=Henry+Lee+Moore&searchType=basic&sequence=0&index=10&state=&date2=1913&proxtext=Henry+Lee+Moore&y=0&x=0&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=4|title=Detective M'Claughry Tells Ax Crime Theory|newspaper=Webster City Freeman |date=27 May 1913}}</ref> Livingston suggested that the prisoner could have something to do with the string of axe murders, which, coupled with the coincidental timing that Moore had just been released at the start of the spree, led McClaughry to propose this theory.<ref name=SK/><ref name=tell/> According to it, Moore was possibly responsible for these murders:<ref name=SK/>\n* Burnham-Wayne Murders (September 17, 1911, in [[Colorado Springs, Colorado]]): Henry F. Wayne, his wife and child, along with the visiting Mrs. Burnham and her two children, were killed at the Waynes' home. Arthur Burnham, the husband of one of the victims, was arrested on suspicion but later released due to lack of evidence. He later died from [[tuberculosis]], still protesting his innocence.\n* Dawson Murders (October 1911, in [[Monmouth, Illinois]]): M. E. Dawson, along with his wife and daughter, were killed with an axe.\n* Showman Murders (October 1911, in [[Ellsworth, Kansas]]): William Showman, along with his wife and three children, were also killed with an axe.\n* Hudson Murders (June 1912, in [[Paola, Kansas]]): Roland Hudson and his wife were killed with an axe.\n* [[Villisca axe murders]] (June 10-11, 1912 in [[Villisca, Iowa]]): the Moore Family (no relation to Henry Lee Moore), as well as two visiting girls named Ina Mae and Lena Stillinger, were brutally killed at the Moores' home.\n\nMcClaughry's theory was overblown by the contemporary media, who claimed that he was stating it as fact and not speculation.<ref name=tell/> An inquest was even started by Police Chief Burno, of Colorado Springs, into the Burnham-Wayne murders, as a man resembling Moore was seen in the city following the grisly killings, but had quickly left and was never seen again.<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn90051521/1913-05-09/ed-1/seq-1/#date1=1912&sort=date&rows=20&words=Henry+Lee+Moore&searchType=basic&sequence=0&index=4&state=&date2=1913&proxtext=Henry+Lee+Moore&y=0&x=0&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=3|title=Axeman Murder Probe Revived At The Springs|newspaper=The Chronicle News |date=9 May 1913}}</ref> However, this was later discredited by M. F. Amrine, Superintendent of the Kansas State Reformatory, who reported that Moore was corresponding with him at the time of the murders, and that Henry was at home in Columbia.<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn99021999/1913-05-27/ed-1/seq-2/#date1=1912&sort=date&rows=20&words=Henry+Lee+Moore&searchType=basic&sequence=0&index=11&state=&date2=1913&proxtext=Henry+Lee+Moore&y=0&x=0&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=4|title=Alibi Established For Alleged Axeman|newspaper=[[Omaha Daily Bee]] |date=27 May 1913}}</ref>\n\nA similar inquest was also initiated by Chief Chargeois, for a 1911 axe murder that took place in [[Lafayette, Louisiana]]. Although [[Clementine Barnabet]] and one of her followers were suspected of that crime, the man had already been imprisoned at the time of the killings. The result from the investigation is currently unknown, but it is presumed that it was called off.<ref>{{Citeweb|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn88064402/1913-05-23/ed-1/seq-2/#date1=1912&sort=date&rows=20&words=Henry+Lee+Moore&searchType=basic&sequence=0&index=6&state=&date2=1913&proxtext=Henry+Lee+Moore&y=0&x=0&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=4|title=Working On Axe Murders|newspaper=The Rice Belt Journal |date=23 May 1913}}</ref>\n\nIn regard to the Villisca murders, few of the residents believed the theory.<ref name=calm>{{Citeweb|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85050913/1913-05-13/ed-1/seq-8/#date1=1912&sort=date&rows=20&words=Henry+Lee+Moore&searchType=basic&sequence=0&index=6&state=&date2=1913&proxtext=Henry+Lee+Moore&y=0&x=0&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=3|title=Theory of Crime Calmly Received|newspaper=Webster City Freeman |date=13 May 1913}}</ref> However, according to Joseph Stillinger, father of the killed Lena, claimed that Moore very much resembled a man that once worked for him.<ref name=clew>{{Citeweb|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn90061371/1913-05-14/ed-1/seq-2/#date1=1912&sort=date&rows=20&words=Henry+Lee+Moore&searchType=basic&sequence=0&index=11&state=&date2=1913&proxtext=Henry+Lee+Moore&y=0&x=0&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=3|title=Trace Clew to Ax Murder|newspaper=Potosi Journal |date=14 May 1913}}</ref> That man, who had given his name as \"Hellum\", was hired in April 1912, and worked for only a week before disappearing.<ref name=calm/> Stillinger and an officer later went on to confront Moore in prison, but, most likely, the mysterious man was not Henry Lee Moore.<ref name=clew/>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of serial killers in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://murderpedia.org/male.M/m/moore-henry-lee.htm Murderpedia Article]\n* [https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/182234612/henry-lee-moore FindAGrave Memorial]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lee Moore, Henry}}\n[[Category:1874 births]]\n[[Category:Date of death unknown]]\n[[Category:20th-century criminals]]\n[[Category:Male serial killers]]\n[[Category:American serial killers]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by Missouri]]\n[[Category:People convicted of forgery]]\n[[Category:Violence against women in the United States]]\n[[Category:Axe murder]]\n[[Category:Familicides]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of Missouri]]\n[[Category:People from Boone County, Missouri]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo/generalfixes, replaced: quicky \u2192 quickly", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_Lee_Moore"}
{"title_page": "San Filippo Neri in Via Giulia", "text_new": "{{Infobox religious building\n| building_name=Church of Saint Philip Neri<br><small>{{lang|it|Chiesa di San Filippo Neri}}</small>\n| image=Regola - S. Filippo Neri.JPG\n| image_size=300px\n| caption=The facade of the building along Via Giulia\n| location= [[Rome]], Italy\n| municipality = [[Regola]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|41|53|49.8|N|12|28|2.8|E|region:IT-RM_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n| geo = \n| religious_affiliation=[[Roman Catholic]]\n| rite=\n| province=\n| district=\n| consecration_year= 1623\n| founded_by=Rutilio Brandi\n| status=Association Church\n| functional_status = Desecrated in 1938\n| patron = [[Saint Trophimus]]</br>[[Philip Neri]]\n| leadership=\n| website=\n| architect=[[Filippo Raguzzini]]\n| architecture_type=\n| architecture_style= [[Baroque]]\n| specifications=yes\n| facade_direction= Southwest\n| groundbreaking= 1623\n| year_completed= 1768\n| construction_cost= 500 scudi (renovation in 1728)\n| capacity=\n| length= \n| width=\n| width_nave=\n| height_max=\n| materials=Stone, [[Brickwork]]\n}}\n'''San Filippo Neri''' is a desecrated church in [[Rome]], important for historical and artistic reasons. The church, facing the [[Via Giulia]], was built during the [[Italian Baroque|Baroque age]]. San Filippo was supposed to be demolished together with the surrounding neighborhood in the late 1930s, but due to the onset of WWII the demolition was halted. Abandoned and desecrated after the war, it has been restored in 2000, but maintains a secular usage and is not accessible.\n\n==Location==\n[[File:Nolli 1748 San Filippo Neri in Via Giulia.JPG|thumb|left|San Filippo Neri (red arrow) and its Oratory (blue arrow) in their original context in the map of Rome of [[Giambattista Nolli]] (1748)]]\nThe church is located in [[Rome]]'s [[Regola]] [[rioni of Rome|rione]], about halfway down [[Via Giulia]] (at the n. 134B), its facade facing west-southwest, in a neighborhood still devastated by the demolitions of the 1930s.\n\n==Denominations==\nThe church, originally dedicated to [[Saint Trophimus]], was then dedicated to Philip Neri and, because of its tiny area, nicknamed by the roman populace \"San Filippino\" (\"Little Saint Philip\").<ref name=arm422/>\n\n==History==\nThe church was erected in 1623 (or, according to another source, in 1603)<ref name=bu705/> along [[via Giulia]].<ref name=pie7916>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 16</ref> The building's client was Rutilio Brandi, a [[Grand Duchy of Tuscany|Tuscan]] glove maker native of [[San Gimignano]].<ref name=pie7916/> Brandi was ''penitente'' of [[Philip Neri]] and  ''Governatore'' of the \"Compagnia delle Santissime Piaghe di Ges\u00f9\" (\"Company of the most holy wounds of [[Jesus]]\"), an institute founded in 1617 and whose members were Florentines living in Rome.<ref name=pie7916/><ref name=arm422>Armellini (1891), p. 422</ref> Since he was ill with [[gout]], Brandi had the church [[dedication|dedicated]] to [[Saint Trophimus]], the protector of the gouties.<ref name=pie7916/> Moreover, in the building which embeds the church Brandi founded two charitable works: a little hospital for priests, and an institute for poor girls, dedicated to Philip Neri.<ref name=pie7918/><ref name=arm422/><ref name=del476>Delli (1988), p. 476</ref> Because of that, the shrine's dedication changed with time to [[San Filippo Neri]], the \"apostle of Rome\".<ref name=pie7916/><ref name=arm422/>\n\nIn 1728 the church was restored by [[Filippo Raguzzini]] on behalf of [[Pope Benedict XIII]] (r. 1724-1730); the main work was the new facade, erected between May and October 1728 with a total expense of 500 ''[[Italian scudo|scudi]]''.<ref name=pie7916/> The church facade was demolished again and rebuilt between 1767 and 1768 according to a project of [[Giovanni Francesco Fiori]], in an [[Eclecticism in art|eclectic]] style between [[Roman Baroque|Baroque]] and [[Neoclassical architecture|Neoclassic]].<ref name=dbi>{{cite encyclopedia |url=http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/giovanni-francesco-fiori_(Dizionario-Biografico)/|title=Fiori, Giovanni Francesco|encyclopedia=Dizionario Biografico degli Italiani |first=Tommaso|last=Manfredi|volume=48 |year=1997|language=it}}</ref>\n\nIn 1797, when the French because of the [[treaty of Tolentino]] pretended a large amount of money from the Pope, San Filippo was the only church in Rome to keep its silver [[reliquary]], since the [[Rector (ecclesiastical)|rector]] of the church refused to give it to [[Pius VI]] (r. 1775-1799).<ref name=del476/><ref name=arm422/>\n\nSince it is only about 100 metres from the [[Tiber]], the church was severely damaged during a flood in 1853,<ref name=bu705/> and due to that was restored under [[Pope Pius IX]] (r. 1846-1878) in the same year.<ref name=pie7916/>\n\nAs part of the demolition works ordered by [[Benito Mussolini]] <ref name=bu705/> in 1938 for the construction of a wide avenue between [[Ponte Mazzini]] and the [[Santa Maria in Vallicella|Chiesa Nuova]],<ref>Mazzotta (2014), pp. 185-187</ref> almost all the buildings around the church were demolished, and the church itself, desecrated, was spared only because of the project stop due to the beginning of WWII.<ref name=pie7916/> After that, the works of art disappeared into hitherto unknown hands or are completely lost.<ref name=bu705/> The building then fell into disrepair:<ref name=bu705/> it served as a wood storage <ref name=bu705/> and as a deposit for the fruit and vegetables street market of nearby ''vicolo della Moretta''. In the 1960s all the windows were smashed,<ref name=bu705/> the fa\u00e7ade deteriorated and the portal was walled up; this condition lasted several decades. In 2000 the edifice has been restored, but its usage remains profane<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/dealvariis/albums/72157619990091265/with/14918292589/|author=Alvaro de Alvariis|title=S. Filippo Neri|website=flickr.com|access-date=3 April 2020|language=Italian}}</ref> and is not accessible.\n\n==Description==\n===Architecture===\n[[File:San Filippo Neri in Via Giulia (altorilievo).jpg|thumb|The stucco medallion on the facade]]\nThe facade of Fiori is a three-axis and two-storey construction.<ref name=bu705>Buchowiecki (1967), p. 705</ref> The three axes are formed by [[giant order]] [[lesene]]s of a variant of the [[ionic order]].<ref name=bu705/> Between the volutes of the capitals are [[festoon]]s.<ref name=bu705/> The [[portal (architecture)|portal]] is vaulted by a continuous segmented arch [[tympanum (architecture)|tympanum]], the [[Bay (architecture)|bays]] of the side axes are simply segmented.<ref name=bu705/> On the first floor, the central axis juts out similarly to an [[avant-corps]], and the element thus created contains a high-oval [[stucco]] [[Medallion (architecture)|medallion]] representing ''Saint Philip welcomed in the heaven by the Virgin and a glory of [[cherub]]s'', sided by windows decorated by stucco figures.<ref name=pie7916/><ref name=pie7918>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 18</ref> The side windows are surmounted by protruding segmented arched tympani.<ref name=bu706/>\n\nThe [[architrave]] protruding above the architectonic elements is adorned with the dedication inscription ''DEO.IN.HONOREM.S.PHILIPPI.NERII.DICATUM''.<ref name=bu706/> Above it, there is a triangular protruding tympanum in a [[Cartouche (design)|cartouche]] (from which [[garland]]s run down on both sides) containing  the [[coat of arms]] of the ''compagnia''.<ref name=pie7918/><ref name=bu706/>\n\nOn the facade facing Via Giulia, the building bears a marble property table with the motto of the ''compagnia'': ''Plagis plaga curatur'' (\"The plagues of the soul are cured with the calamities\").<ref name=pie7918/>\n\n===Interior===\nThe interior dimensions of the small church are 14 meters in length and 8.40 meters in width.<ref name=bu706>Buchowiecki (1967), p. 706</ref> The interior of the building has a single [[nave]] and three [[Bay (architecture)|bays]].<ref name=bu706/> A peculiarity is that the central axis is not, as expected, at right angles to the fa\u00e7ade, but bends about 20 degrees to the south, which is due to the difficult spatial conditions at the time of construction.<ref name=bu706/> There are three very narrow chapels on each side.<ref name=bu706/> The [[Vault (architecture)|vault]]ing consists of transverse and staggered [[barrel vault]]s, which thus decrease in height towards the [[Choir (architecture)|choir room]].<ref name=bu706/> The transversal arches between the barrels are supported by [[pilaster]]s of [[Tuscan order]].<ref name=bu706/> \n\nThe church had three [[Altar in the Catholic Church|altars]]: the side altars were consecrated by [[Pope Benedict XIII]] in 1728.<ref name=pie7916/> The right was adorned with a medieval relief originally in the [[vatican grotto]] representing the [[Crucifixion in the arts|crucifixion]], while the left one was surmounted by a painting by Filippo Zucchetti representing ''Saint Trophimus healing the gouties''.<ref name=pie7916/> On the main altar lay originally a copy of a painting by [[Guido Reni]] representing ''Saint Philip'' (the original is at the [[Chiesa Nuova]]).<ref name=pie7916/> In 1853 this was substituted with a painting by [[Albert Christoph Dies]] from a drawing by [[Tommaso Minardi]] representing ''Saint Philip brought to the Heaven by the angels''.<ref name=bu706/><ref name=pie7916/>\n\n==Oratory==\nAlong the nearby ''vicolo del malpasso'', adjoining the north side of the church, lay the small [[Oratory (worship)|oratory]] - now demolished - <ref name=bu706/> of the ''Compagnia delle Santissime Piaghe di Ges\u00f9'', which was also in a dilapidated state.<ref name=pie7918/> It hosted a painting attributed to [[Federico Zuccari]], with subject ''Christ on the [[mount of Olives]]''.<ref name=pie7918/>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book\n | author=Mariano Armellini\n | title = Le chiese di Roma dal secolo IV al XIX\n | year = 1891\n | url=http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/I/Gazetteer/Places/Europe/Italy/Lazio/Roma/Rome/churches/_Texts/Armellini/ARMCHI*/home.html\n | language=Italian\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | author=Pietrangeli, Carlo\n | title=Guide rionali di Roma\n | volume=Regola (III)\n | publisher=Fratelli Palombi Editori\n | location=Roma\n | edition=2\n | year=1979\n | language=Italian\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | author= Walter Buchowiecki\n | title= Handbuch der Kirchen Roms\n | volume = 1 \n | publisher= Verlag Br\u00fcder Hollinek\n | location = Wien \n | year = 1967\n | language=German\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | author= Sergio Delli\n |title=Le strade di Roma\n |publisher=Newton & Compton\n |location=Roma\n |year=1988\n |language=it\n}}\n* {{Cite publication|first=Bartolomeo|last=Mazzotta|title=Dall'archivio Cederna: le chiese distrutte a Roma durante il ventennio fascista (1922-1943)|editor=AA. VV.|work=Palazzo dei Convertendi:storia e restauro 1500-2014|publisher=Gangemi|location=Roma|year=2014|language=it |isbn=978-88-492-2958-5}}\n{{commons category}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Filippo Neri in Via Giulia}}\n[[Category:Churches of Rome (rione Regola)]]\n[[Category:Baroque church buildings in Italy]]\n[[Category:17th-century Roman Catholic church buildings]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic churches completed in 1768]]\n[[Category:Deconsecrated Roman Catholic churches in Rome]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox religious building\n| building_name=Church of Saint Philip Neri<br><small>{{lang|it|Chiesa di San Filippo Neri}}</small>\n| image=Regola - S. Filippo Neri.JPG\n| image_size=300px\n| caption=The facade of the building along Via Giulia\n| location= [[Rome]], Italy\n| municipality = [[Regola]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|41|53|49.8|N|12|28|2.8|E|region:IT-RM_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n| geo = \n| religious_affiliation=[[Roman Catholic]]\n| rite=\n| province=\n| district=\n| consecration_year= 1623\n| founded_by=Rutilio Brandi\n| status=Association Church\n| functional_status = Desecrated in 1938\n| patron = [[Saint Trophimus]]</br>[[Philip Neri]]\n| leadership=\n| website=\n| architect=[[Filippo Raguzzini]]\n| architecture_type=\n| architecture_style= [[Baroque]]\n| specifications=yes\n| facade_direction= Southwest\n| groundbreaking= 1623\n| year_completed= 1768\n| construction_cost= 500 scudi (renovation in 1728)\n| capacity=\n| length= \n| width=\n| width_nave=\n| height_max=\n| materials=Stone, [[Brickwork]]\n}}\n'''San Filippo Neri''' is a desecrated church in [[Rome]], important for historical and artistic reasons. The church, facing the [[Via Giulia]], was built during the [[Italian Baroque|Baroque age]]. San Filippo was supposed to be demolished together with the surrounding neighborhood in the late 1930s, but due to the onset of WWII the demolition was halted. Abandoned and desecrated after the war, it has been restored in 2000, but maintains a secular usage and is not accessible.\n\n==Location==\n[[File:Nolli 1748 San Filippo Neri in Via Giulia.JPG|thumb|left|San Filippo Neri (red arrow) and its Oratory (blue arrow) in their original context in the map of Rome of [[Giambattista Nolli]] (1748)]]\nThe church is located in [[Rome]]'s [[Regola]] [[rioni of Rome|rione]], about halfway down [[Via Giulia]] (at the n. 134B), its facade facing west-southwest, in a neighborhood still devastated by the demolitions of the 1930s.\n\n==Denominations==\nThe church, originally dedicated to [[Saint Trophimus]], was then dedicated to Philip Neri and, because of its tiny area, nicknamed by the roman populace \"San Filippino\" (\"Little Saint Philip\").<ref name=arm422/>\n\n==History==\nThe church was erected in 1623 (or, according to another source, in 1603)<ref name=bu705/> along [[via Giulia]].<ref name=pie7916>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 16</ref> The building's client was Rutilio Brandi, a [[Grand Duchy of Tuscany|Tuscan]] glove maker native of [[San Gimignano]].<ref name=pie7916/> Brandi was ''penitente'' of [[Philip Neri]] and  ''Governatore'' of the \"Compagnia delle Santissime Piaghe di Ges\u00f9\" (\"Company of the most holy wounds of [[Jesus]]\"), an institute founded in 1617 and whose members were Florentines living in Rome.<ref name=pie7916/><ref name=arm422>Armellini (1891), p. 422</ref> Since he was ill with [[gout]], Brandi had the church [[dedication|dedicated]] to [[Saint Trophimus]], the protector of the gouties.<ref name=pie7916/> Moreover, in the building which embeds the church Brandi founded two charitable works: a little hospital for priests, and an institute for poor girls, dedicated to Philip Neri.<ref name=pie7918/><ref name=arm422/><ref name=del476>Delli (1988), p. 476</ref> Because of that, the shrine's dedication changed with time to [[San Filippo Neri]], the \"apostle of Rome\".<ref name=pie7916/><ref name=arm422/>\n\nIn 1728 the church was restored by [[Filippo Raguzzini]] on behalf of [[Pope Benedict XIII]] (r. 1724-1730); the main work was the new facade, erected between May and October 1728 with a total expense of 500 ''[[Italian scudo|scudi]]''.<ref name=pie7916/> The church facade was demolished again and rebuilt between 1767 and 1768 according to a project of [[Giovanni Francesco Fiori]], in an [[Eclecticism in art|eclectic]] style between [[Roman Baroque|Baroque]] and [[Neoclassical architecture|Neoclassic]].<ref name=dbi>{{cite encyclopedia |url=http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/giovanni-francesco-fiori_(Dizionario-Biografico)/|title=Fiori, Giovanni Francesco|encyclopedia=Dizionario Biografico degli Italiani |first=Tommaso|last=Manfredi|volume=48 |year=1997|language=it}}</ref>\n\nIn 1797, when the French because of the [[treaty of Tolentino]] pretended a large amount of money from the Pope, San Filippo was the only church in Rome to keep its silver [[reliquary]], since the [[Rector (ecclesiastical)|rector]] of the church refused to give it to [[Pius VI]] (r. 1775-1799).<ref name=del476/><ref name=arm422/>\n\nSince it is only about 100 metres from the [[Tiber]], the church was severely damaged during a flood in 1853,<ref name=bu705/> and due to that was restored under [[Pope Pius IX]] (r. 1846-1878) in the same year.<ref name=pie7916/>\n\nAs part of the demolition works ordered by [[Benito Mussolini]] <ref name=bu705/> in 1938 for the construction of a wide avenue between [[Ponte Mazzini]] and the [[Santa Maria in Vallicella|Chiesa Nuova]],<ref>Mazzotta (2014), pp. 185-187</ref> almost all the buildings around the church were demolished, and the church itself, desecrated, was spared only because of the stop of the project due to the beginning of WWII.<ref name=pie7916/> After that, the works of art disappeared into hitherto unknown hands or are completely lost.<ref name=bu705/> The building then fell into disrepair:<ref name=bu705/> it served as a wood storage <ref name=bu705/> and as a deposit for the fruit and vegetables street market of nearby ''vicolo della Moretta''. In the 1960s all the windows were smashed,<ref name=bu705/> the fa\u00e7ade deteriorated and the portal was walled up; this condition lasted several decades. In 2000 the edifice has been restored, but its usage remains profane<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/dealvariis/albums/72157619990091265/with/14918292589/|author=Alvaro de Alvariis|title=S. Filippo Neri|website=flickr.com|access-date=3 April 2020|language=Italian}}</ref> and is not accessible.\n\n==Description==\n===Architecture===\n[[File:San Filippo Neri in Via Giulia (altorilievo).jpg|thumb|The stucco medallion on the facade]]\nThe facade of Fiori is a three-axis and two-storey construction.<ref name=bu705>Buchowiecki (1967), p. 705</ref> The three axes are formed by [[giant order]] [[lesene]]s of a variant of the [[ionic order]].<ref name=bu705/> Between the volutes of the capitals are [[festoon]]s.<ref name=bu705/> The [[portal (architecture)|portal]] is vaulted by a continuous segmented arch [[tympanum (architecture)|tympanum]], the [[Bay (architecture)|bays]] of the side axes are simply segmented.<ref name=bu705/> On the first floor, the central axis juts out similarly to an [[avant-corps]], and the element thus created contains a high-oval [[stucco]] [[Medallion (architecture)|medallion]] representing ''Saint Philip welcomed in the heaven by the Virgin and a glory of [[cherub]]s'', sided by windows decorated by stucco figures.<ref name=pie7916/><ref name=pie7918>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 18</ref> The side windows are surmounted by protruding segmented arched tympani.<ref name=bu706/>\n\nThe [[architrave]] protruding above the architectonic elements is adorned with the dedication inscription ''DEO.IN.HONOREM.S.PHILIPPI.NERII.DICATUM''.<ref name=bu706/> Above it, there is a triangular protruding tympanum in a [[Cartouche (design)|cartouche]] (from which [[garland]]s run down on both sides) containing  the [[coat of arms]] of the ''compagnia''.<ref name=pie7918/><ref name=bu706/>\n\nOn the facade facing Via Giulia, the building bears a marble property table with the motto of the ''compagnia'': ''Plagis plaga curatur'' (\"The plagues of the soul are cured with the calamities\").<ref name=pie7918/>\n\n===Interior===\nThe interior dimensions of the small church are 14 meters in length and 8.40 meters in width.<ref name=bu706>Buchowiecki (1967), p. 706</ref> The interior of the building has a single [[nave]] and three [[Bay (architecture)|bays]].<ref name=bu706/> A peculiarity is that the central axis is not, as expected, at right angles to the fa\u00e7ade, but bends about 20 degrees to the south, which is due to the difficult spatial conditions at the time of construction.<ref name=bu706/> There are three very narrow chapels on each side.<ref name=bu706/> The [[Vault (architecture)|vault]]ing consists of transverse and staggered [[barrel vault]]s, which thus decrease in height towards the [[Choir (architecture)|choir room]].<ref name=bu706/> The transversal arches between the barrels are supported by [[pilaster]]s of [[Tuscan order]].<ref name=bu706/> \n\nThe church had three [[Altar in the Catholic Church|altars]]: the side altars were consecrated by [[Pope Benedict XIII]] in 1728.<ref name=pie7916/> The right was adorned with a medieval relief originally in the [[vatican grotto]] representing the [[Crucifixion in the arts|crucifixion]], while the left one was surmounted by a painting by Filippo Zucchetti representing ''Saint Trophimus healing the gouties''.<ref name=pie7916/> On the main altar lay originally a copy of a painting by [[Guido Reni]] representing ''Saint Philip'' (the original is at the [[Chiesa Nuova]]).<ref name=pie7916/> In 1853 this was substituted with a painting by [[Albert Christoph Dies]] from a drawing by [[Tommaso Minardi]] representing ''Saint Philip brought to the Heaven by the angels''.<ref name=bu706/><ref name=pie7916/>\n\n==Oratory==\nAlong the nearby ''vicolo del malpasso'', adjoining the north side of the church, lay the small [[Oratory (worship)|oratory]] - now demolished - <ref name=bu706/> of the ''Compagnia delle Santissime Piaghe di Ges\u00f9'', which was also in a dilapidated state.<ref name=pie7918/> It hosted a painting attributed to [[Federico Zuccari]], with subject ''Christ on the [[mount of Olives]]''.<ref name=pie7918/>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book\n | author=Mariano Armellini\n | title = Le chiese di Roma dal secolo IV al XIX\n | year = 1891\n | url=http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/I/Gazetteer/Places/Europe/Italy/Lazio/Roma/Rome/churches/_Texts/Armellini/ARMCHI*/home.html\n | language=Italian\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | author=Pietrangeli, Carlo\n | title=Guide rionali di Roma\n | volume=Regola (III)\n | publisher=Fratelli Palombi Editori\n | location=Roma\n | edition=2\n | year=1979\n | language=Italian\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | author= Walter Buchowiecki\n | title= Handbuch der Kirchen Roms\n | volume = 1 \n | publisher= Verlag Br\u00fcder Hollinek\n | location = Wien \n | year = 1967\n | language=German\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | author= Sergio Delli\n |title=Le strade di Roma\n |publisher=Newton & Compton\n |location=Roma\n |year=1988\n |language=it\n}}\n* {{Cite publication|first=Bartolomeo|last=Mazzotta|title=Dall'archivio Cederna: le chiese distrutte a Roma durante il ventennio fascista (1922-1943)|editor=AA. VV.|work=Palazzo dei Convertendi:storia e restauro 1500-2014|publisher=Gangemi|location=Roma|year=2014|language=it |isbn=978-88-492-2958-5}}\n{{commons category}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Filippo Neri in Via Giulia}}\n[[Category:Churches of Rome (rione Regola)]]\n[[Category:Baroque church buildings in Italy]]\n[[Category:17th-century Roman Catholic church buildings]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic churches completed in 1768]]\n[[Category:Deconsecrated Roman Catholic churches in Rome]]\n", "name_user": "Alessandro57", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/San_Filippo_Neri_in_Via_Giulia"}
{"title_page": "Daniel Okrent", "text_new": "{{short description|American magazine editor}}\n{{use American English|date=July 2015}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=July 2015}}\n'''Daniel Okrent''' (born April 2, 1948) is an American writer and [[editing|editor]]. He is best known for having served as the first [[public editor]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' newspaper, inventing [[Rotisserie League Baseball]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nola.com/sports/fantasy/index.ssf/2011/03/ready_for_your_fantasy_basebal.html|title=Ready for your fantasy baseball draft? Here are some simple rules to live by|last=Derry|first=Jim|date=March 28, 2011|work=[[The Times-Picayune]]|access-date= April 24, 2011}}</ref> and for writing several books (such as ''Last Call: The Rise and Fall of Prohibition'', which served as a major source for the 2011 [[Ken Burns]]/[[Lynn Novick]] miniseries ''[[Prohibition (miniseries)|Prohibition]])''. In November 2011, ''Last Call'' won the Albert J. Beveridge prize, awarded by the [[American Historical Association]] to the year's best book of American history. His most recent book, published May 2019, is ''The Guarded Gate: Bigotry, Eugenics, and the Law That Kept Two Generations of Jews, Italians, and Other European Immigrants Out of America''.<ref>{{cite episode |last=Gross |first=Terry |authorlink=Terry Gross |air-date=May 8, 2019 |title=Eugenics, anti-immigration laws of the past still resonate today, journalist says |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/05/08/721371176/eugenics-anti-immigration-laws-of-the-past-still-resonate-today-journalist-says |series=[[Fresh Air]] |network=[[NPR]]}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn to a [[American Jews|Jewish]] family<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Okrent  |first=Daniel |title=Kvelling in Their Seats - A first-time producer on what it took to stage Old Jews Telling Jokes   |magazine=[[New York Magazine]]|date=April 29, 2012|url=http://nymag.com/arts/theater/features/old-jews-telling-jokes-2012-5/  }}</ref> in [[Detroit|Detroit, Michigan]], Okrent graduated from [[Cass Technical High School]] in Detroit<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,275003,00.html | work= [[Entertainment Weekly]] | title=Getting the 'Lowdown' | date= January 7, 2000}}</ref> and in 1965 from the [[University of Michigan]], where he worked on the university's student newspaper ''[[The Michigan Daily]]''.\n\n==Career==\nMost of his career has been spent as an editor, at such places as [[Alfred A. Knopf]]; [[Harcourt Trade Publishers|Harcourt, Brace, Jovanovich]]; ''[[Esquire Magazine]]''; ''[[New England Monthly]]''; ''[[Life Magazine]]''; and [[Time, Inc.]]\n\nHis book ''Great Fortune: The Epic of [[Rockefeller Center]]'' (Viking, 2003) was a finalist for the [[Pulitzer Prize for History]].\n\nIn October 2003, Okrent was named [[public editor]] for ''[[The New York Times]]'' following the [[Jayson Blair]] scandal. He held this position until May 2005.\n\nOkrent and [[Peter Gethers]], having acquired the theatrical rights to the site and name of the web series ''[[Old Jews Telling Jokes]]'', co-wrote and co-produced a revue of that name.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Okrent|first1=Daniel|title=Kvelling in Their Seats|url=http://nymag.com/arts/theater/features/old-jews-telling-jokes-2012-5/|website=New York Magazine|publisher=New York Magazine|accessdate=25 December 2016}}</ref> It opened at the [[Westside Theatre]] in Manhattan on May 20, 2012.\n\nOn May 3, 2014, the University of Michigan awarded Okrent an honorary degree, Doctor of Humane Letters.\n\nSince 2017, Okrent has been listed on the Advisory Board of the [[Secular Coalition for America]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.secular.org/board |title=Board |website=secular.org |publisher=[[Secular Coalition for America]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170104233603/https://www.secular.org/board |archivedate=2017-01-04 |accessdate=2018-10-29}}</ref>\n\n== {{Anchor|Okrent's Law}} {{Anchor|Okrent's law}} Okrent's law ==\n{{See also|False balance|Journalistic objectivity|View from nowhere}}\nHe formulated what has become known as \"Okrent's law\" in an interview comment he made about his new job. It states: \"The pursuit of balance can create imbalance because sometimes something is true\", referring to the phenomenon of the press providing legitimacy to unsupported fringe viewpoints in an [[Argument to moderation|effort to appear even-handed]].<ref>{{cite web\n| last1=Pearlman\n| first1=Jeff\n| author1link=Jeff Pearlman\n| title=Daniel Okrent\n| url=http://www.jeffpearlman.com/the-quaz-qa-daniel-okrent/\n| website=Jeff Pearlman\n| publisher=Jeff Pearlman\n| access-date= August 8, 2014\n| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130106205742/http://www.jeffpearlman.com/the-quaz-qa-daniel-okrent/\n| archive-date= January 6, 2013\n| date= October 11, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal\n| title=The New Yorker\n| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bAXkAAAAMAAJ&q=%22The+pursuit+of+balance+can+create+imbalance+because+sometimes+something+is+true%22\n| date= May 24, 2004\n| publisher=F-R Publishing Corporation\n| page=244\n| volume=80\n| series=Issues 1\u201310}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=[[Old Jews Telling Jokes | Old Jews Telling Jokes: 5,000 Years of Funny Bits and Not-So-Kosher Laughs]]|last1=Hoffman|first1=Sam|last2=Spiegelman|first2=Eric|date=2010|publisher=Random House Publishing Group|isbn=9780345522450|edition=Trade Paperback|page=198}}<!--| access-date= August 8, 2014--></ref><ref>{{cite book\n| last1=Schwarz\n| first1=Daniel R.\n| author1link=Daniel R. Schwarz\n| title=Endtimes? Crises and Turmoil at the New York Times 1999-2009\n| date=2012\n| publisher= [[State University of New York Press]]\n| page=205\n| edition=Albany: Excelsior Editions\n| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=v_qGAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA205\n| access-date= August 8, 2014\n| chapter=6 Counter-Reformation or the Way We Are (I)\n| oclc=702357541}}</ref>\n\n==Baseball==\nOkrent invented [[Rotisserie League Baseball]], the best-known form of [[fantasy baseball]], in 1979. The name comes from the fact that he proposed the idea to his friends while dining at La R\u00f4tisserie Fran\u00e7aise restaurant in New York City. Okrent's team in the Rotisserie League was called the \"Okrent Fenokees\", a pun on the [[Okefenokee Swamp]]. He was one of the first two people inducted into the Fantasy Sports Hall of Fame.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fsta.org/blog/hall-of-fame |title=Fantasy Sports Hall of Fame |website=fsta.org}}</ref> Okrent was still playing Rotisserie as of 2009 under the team name Dan Druffs. Despite having been credited with inventing fantasy baseball he has never been able to win a Rotisserie League. His exploits of inventing Rotisserie League Baseball were chronicled in ''Silly Little Game'', part of the [[ESPN]] ''[[30 for 30]]'' documentary series, in [[2010 in sports|2010]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://30for30.espn.com/film/silly-little-game.html |title=30 for 30 |publisher=[[ESPN]] |accessdate=April 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOkrent is also credited with inventing the baseball stat, [[Walks plus hits per inning pitched|WHIP]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Di Fino |first=Nando |date=August 3, 2009 |title=Dan Okrent Invented WHIP Statistic, Fantasy Baseball |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970204619004574318690805089868 |accessdate=2017-12-24}}</ref> At the time he referred to it as IPRAT, signifying \"Innings Pitched Ratio\".\n\nIn May 1981, Okrent wrote and ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' published \"He Does It by the Numbers\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Okrent |first=Daniel |date=25 May 1981 |title=He Does It By The Numbers |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1124493/index.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090813032532/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1124493/index.htm |website=sportsillustrated.cnn.com |publisher=[[Sports Illustrated]] |archivedate=2009-08-13 |accessdate=2017-12-24}}</ref> This profile of the then-unknown [[Bill James]] launched James's career as baseball's foremost analyst.<ref>{{cite book |last=Chafets |first=Ze'ev |date=2009 |title=Cooperstown Confidential: Heroes, Rogues, and the Inside Story of the Baseball Hall of Fame |location=New York |publisher=[[Bloomsbury USA]] |page=[//books.google.com/books?id=OEXDt0Os5aQC&pg=PA44 44] |isbn=9781596915459 |oclc=305422137}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, Okrent was filmed for his in-depth knowledge of baseball history for the [[Ken Burns]] documentary ''[[Baseball (TV series)|Baseball]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dan Okrent: The Origins of Rotisserie Baseball \u2013 The Tenth Inning |url=http://www.pbs.org/video/the-tenth-inning-the-tenth-inning-interview-extras-rotisserie/ |website=pbs.org |accessdate=2017-12-24}}</ref> During the nine-part series, a red-sweater-wearing Okrent delivered a detailed analysis of the cultural aspects of the national pastime, including a comparison of the dramatic Game 6 of the [[1975 World Series]] between the [[Boston Red Sox]] and [[Cincinnati Reds]] to the conflict and character development in [[Russian literature|Russian novels]].\n\n==The Death of Print==\nIn the late 1990s, as editor of new media at [[Time Inc.]], Okrent wrote about the future of magazine publishing.<ref name=\"Lieb\">{{cite journal |last=Lieb |first=Thom |date=March 2001 |title=Q. & A.: Breaking News |journal=The Journal of Electronic Publishing |volume=6 |issue=3 |url=http://quod.lib.umich.edu/j/jep/3336451.0006.306?view=text;rgn=main |doi=10.3998/3336451.0006.306 |accessdate=2016-04-25}}</ref> He believed that the advancement of digital technologies would make it easier for people to read newspapers, magazines and books online.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Nayar|first1=Pramod K.|title=Virtual worlds: culture and politics in the age of cybertechnology|date=2004|publisher=[[Sage Publications]]|location=New Delhi|isbn=9780761932284|page=[//books.google.com/books?id=ksmGAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA117 117]}}</ref> In late 1999, Okrent made a prediction about the future of print media in the Hearst New Media Lecture at the [[Columbia University Graduate School of Journalism|Graduate School of Journalism of Columbia University]].<ref name=\"Lieb\"/> He told his audience: {{Quote|I believe they, and all forms of print, are dead. Finished. Over. Perhaps not in my professional lifetime, but certainly in that of the youngest people in this room. Remove the question mark from the title of this talk. The Death of Print, full stop.<ref>{{cite web |last=Okrent |first=Dan |date=February 2000 |title=The Death of Print? |url=http://digitaljournalist.org/issue0002/okrent.htm |website=digitaljournalist.org |accessdate=2016-04-25}}</ref>}}\n\n==Personal life==\nOkrent has participated in [[LearnedLeague]] under the name \"OkrentD\".<ref>{{cite web |title=LL Profile: OkrentD |url=http://learnedleague.com/profiles.php?okrentd |publisher=[[LearnedLeague]] |accessdate=2014-10-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Kushner |first=Adam B. |date=August 20, 2014 |title=The coolest, weirdest Internet community you'll never be able to join |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/the-coolest-weirdest-internet-community-youll-never-be-able-to-join/2014/08/20/3c3f565e-26eb-11e4-958c-268a320a60ce_story.html |website=washingtonpost.com |publisher=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=2017-12-24}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''The Ultimate Baseball Book'' (co-editor, with Harris Lewine) (1979)\n* ''Nine Innings: The Anatomy of Baseball as Seen Through the Playing of a Single Game'' (1985)\n* ''Baseball Anecdotes'' (co-author, with Steve Wulf) (1987)\n* ''The Way We Were: New England Then, New England Now'' (1988)\n* ''[[Great Fortune: The Epic of Rockefeller Center]]'' (2003)\n* ''Public Editor #1'' (2006)\n* ''Last Call: The Rise and Fall of Prohibition'' (2010)\n* ''The Guarded Gate: Bigotry, Eugenics, and the Law That Kept Two Generations of Jews, Italians, and Other European Immigrants Out of America'' (2019)\n\n==Filmography==\n* ''[[Baseball (documentary)|Baseball]]'' (1994), (2010) | Documentary | Directed by: [[Ken Burns]]\n* ''[[Sweet And Lowdown]]'' (1999) | Role of: A.J. Pickman | Comedy-Drama | Directed by: [[Woody Allen]]\n* ''[[Wordplay (film)|Wordplay]]'' (2006) | Documentary | Directed by: [[Patrick Creadon]]\n* ''[[The Hoax]]'' (2007) | Role of: Real Publisher #1 | Comedy-Drama | Directed by: [[Lasse Hallstr\u00f6m]]\n* ''[[Silly Little Game]]'' (2010) | Documentary | Directed by: Lucas Jansen and Adam Kurland\n* ''[[Prohibition (miniseries)|Prohibition]]'' (2011) | Documentary | Directed by: [[Ken Burns]]\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Biography|Baseball|Journalism}}\n* [[List of people from Detroit]]\n* [[List of people from New York City]]\n* [[List of University of Michigan alumni]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|nm0645711}}\n* {{iobdb name|41415}}\n* {{cite web |last=Roberts |first=Russ |title=Okrent on Prohibition and His Book, ''Last Call'' |url=http://www.econtalk.org/archives/_featuring/daniel_okrent/ |work=[[EconTalk]] |publisher=[[Library of Economics and Liberty]] |authorlink=Russ Roberts |date=June 7, 2010}}\n*{{C-SPAN|Daniel Okrent}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-media}}\n{{S-new}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Public Editor]] for ''[[The New York Times]]''|years=2003\u20132005}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Byron Calame]]}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Okrent, Daniel}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:American book editors]]\n[[Category:American magazine editors]]\n[[Category:Baseball writers]]\n[[Category:Cass Technical High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportswriters from Michigan]]\n[[Category:Sportswriters from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:The New York Times public editors]]\n[[Category:University of Michigan alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from Detroit]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York City]]\n[[Category:American male dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century American dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Jewish American journalists]]\n[[Category:The Michigan Daily alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American magazine editor}}\n{{use American English|date=July 2015}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=July 2015}}\n'''Daniel Okrent''' (born April 2, 1948) is an American writer and [[editing|editor]]. He is best known for having served as the first [[public editor]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' newspaper, inventing [[Rotisserie League Baseball]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nola.com/sports/fantasy/index.ssf/2011/03/ready_for_your_fantasy_basebal.html|title=Ready for your fantasy baseball draft? Here are some simple rules to live by|last=Derry|first=Jim|date=March 28, 2011|work=[[The Times-Picayune]]|access-date= April 24, 2011}}</ref> and for writing several books (such as ''Last Call: The Rise and Fall of Prohibition'', which served as a major source for the 2011 [[Ken Burns]]/[[Lynn Novick]] miniseries ''[[Prohibition (miniseries)|Prohibition]])''. In November 2011, ''Last Call'' won the Albert J. Beveridge prize, awarded by the [[American Historical Association]] to the year's best book of American history. His most recent book, published May 2019, is ''The Guarded Gate: Bigotry, Eugenics, and the Law That Kept Two Generations of Jews, Italians, and Other European Immigrants Out of America''.<ref>{{cite episode |last=Gross |first=Terry |authorlink=Terry Gross |air-date=May 8, 2019 |title=Eugenics, anti-immigration laws of the past still resonate today, journalist says |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/05/08/721371176/eugenics-anti-immigration-laws-of-the-past-still-resonate-today-journalist-says |series=[[Fresh Air]] |network=[[NPR]]}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn to a [[American Jews|Jewish]] family<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Okrent  |first=Daniel |title=Kvelling in Their Seats - A first-time producer on what it took to stage Old Jews Telling Jokes   |magazine=[[New York Magazine]]|date=April 29, 2012|url=http://nymag.com/arts/theater/features/old-jews-telling-jokes-2012-5/  }}</ref> in [[Detroit|Detroit, Michigan]], Okrent graduated from [[Cass Technical High School]] in Detroit<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,275003,00.html | work= [[Entertainment Weekly]] | title=Getting the 'Lowdown' | date= January 7, 2000}}</ref> in 1965 and from the [[University of Michigan]], where he worked on the university's student newspaper ''[[The Michigan Daily]]''.\n\n==Career==\nMost of his career has been spent as an editor, at such places as [[Alfred A. Knopf]]; [[Harcourt Trade Publishers|Harcourt, Brace, Jovanovich]]; ''[[Esquire Magazine]]''; ''[[New England Monthly]]''; ''[[Life Magazine]]''; and [[Time, Inc.]]\n\nHis book ''Great Fortune: The Epic of [[Rockefeller Center]]'' (Viking, 2003) was a finalist for the [[Pulitzer Prize for History]].\n\nIn October 2003, Okrent was named [[public editor]] for ''[[The New York Times]]'' following the [[Jayson Blair]] scandal. He held this position until May 2005.\n\nOkrent and [[Peter Gethers]], having acquired the theatrical rights to the site and name of the web series ''[[Old Jews Telling Jokes]]'', co-wrote and co-produced a revue of that name.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Okrent|first1=Daniel|title=Kvelling in Their Seats|url=http://nymag.com/arts/theater/features/old-jews-telling-jokes-2012-5/|website=New York Magazine|publisher=New York Magazine|accessdate=25 December 2016}}</ref> It opened at the [[Westside Theatre]] in Manhattan on May 20, 2012.\n\nOn May 3, 2014, the University of Michigan awarded Okrent an honorary degree, Doctor of Humane Letters.\n\nSince 2017, Okrent has been listed on the Advisory Board of the [[Secular Coalition for America]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.secular.org/board |title=Board |website=secular.org |publisher=[[Secular Coalition for America]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170104233603/https://www.secular.org/board |archivedate=2017-01-04 |accessdate=2018-10-29}}</ref>\n\n== {{Anchor|Okrent's Law}} {{Anchor|Okrent's law}} Okrent's law ==\n{{See also|False balance|Journalistic objectivity|View from nowhere}}\nHe formulated what has become known as \"Okrent's law\" in an interview comment he made about his new job. It states: \"The pursuit of balance can create imbalance because sometimes something is true\", referring to the phenomenon of the press providing legitimacy to unsupported fringe viewpoints in an [[Argument to moderation|effort to appear even-handed]].<ref>{{cite web\n| last1=Pearlman\n| first1=Jeff\n| author1link=Jeff Pearlman\n| title=Daniel Okrent\n| url=http://www.jeffpearlman.com/the-quaz-qa-daniel-okrent/\n| website=Jeff Pearlman\n| publisher=Jeff Pearlman\n| access-date= August 8, 2014\n| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130106205742/http://www.jeffpearlman.com/the-quaz-qa-daniel-okrent/\n| archive-date= January 6, 2013\n| date= October 11, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal\n| title=The New Yorker\n| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bAXkAAAAMAAJ&q=%22The+pursuit+of+balance+can+create+imbalance+because+sometimes+something+is+true%22\n| date= May 24, 2004\n| publisher=F-R Publishing Corporation\n| page=244\n| volume=80\n| series=Issues 1\u201310}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=[[Old Jews Telling Jokes | Old Jews Telling Jokes: 5,000 Years of Funny Bits and Not-So-Kosher Laughs]]|last1=Hoffman|first1=Sam|last2=Spiegelman|first2=Eric|date=2010|publisher=Random House Publishing Group|isbn=9780345522450|edition=Trade Paperback|page=198}}<!--| access-date= August 8, 2014--></ref><ref>{{cite book\n| last1=Schwarz\n| first1=Daniel R.\n| author1link=Daniel R. Schwarz\n| title=Endtimes? Crises and Turmoil at the New York Times 1999-2009\n| date=2012\n| publisher= [[State University of New York Press]]\n| page=205\n| edition=Albany: Excelsior Editions\n| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=v_qGAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA205\n| access-date= August 8, 2014\n| chapter=6 Counter-Reformation or the Way We Are (I)\n| oclc=702357541}}</ref>\n\n==Baseball==\nOkrent invented [[Rotisserie League Baseball]], the best-known form of [[fantasy baseball]], in 1979. The name comes from the fact that he proposed the idea to his friends while dining at La R\u00f4tisserie Fran\u00e7aise restaurant in New York City. Okrent's team in the Rotisserie League was called the \"Okrent Fenokees\", a pun on the [[Okefenokee Swamp]]. He was one of the first two people inducted into the Fantasy Sports Hall of Fame.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fsta.org/blog/hall-of-fame |title=Fantasy Sports Hall of Fame |website=fsta.org}}</ref> Okrent was still playing Rotisserie as of 2009 under the team name Dan Druffs. Despite having been credited with inventing fantasy baseball he has never been able to win a Rotisserie League. His exploits of inventing Rotisserie League Baseball were chronicled in ''Silly Little Game'', part of the [[ESPN]] ''[[30 for 30]]'' documentary series, in [[2010 in sports|2010]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://30for30.espn.com/film/silly-little-game.html |title=30 for 30 |publisher=[[ESPN]] |accessdate=April 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOkrent is also credited with inventing the baseball stat, [[Walks plus hits per inning pitched|WHIP]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Di Fino |first=Nando |date=August 3, 2009 |title=Dan Okrent Invented WHIP Statistic, Fantasy Baseball |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970204619004574318690805089868 |accessdate=2017-12-24}}</ref> At the time he referred to it as IPRAT, signifying \"Innings Pitched Ratio\".\n\nIn May 1981, Okrent wrote and ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' published \"He Does It by the Numbers\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Okrent |first=Daniel |date=25 May 1981 |title=He Does It By The Numbers |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1124493/index.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090813032532/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1124493/index.htm |website=sportsillustrated.cnn.com |publisher=[[Sports Illustrated]] |archivedate=2009-08-13 |accessdate=2017-12-24}}</ref> This profile of the then-unknown [[Bill James]] launched James's career as baseball's foremost analyst.<ref>{{cite book |last=Chafets |first=Ze'ev |date=2009 |title=Cooperstown Confidential: Heroes, Rogues, and the Inside Story of the Baseball Hall of Fame |location=New York |publisher=[[Bloomsbury USA]] |page=[//books.google.com/books?id=OEXDt0Os5aQC&pg=PA44 44] |isbn=9781596915459 |oclc=305422137}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, Okrent was filmed for his in-depth knowledge of baseball history for the [[Ken Burns]] documentary ''[[Baseball (TV series)|Baseball]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dan Okrent: The Origins of Rotisserie Baseball \u2013 The Tenth Inning |url=http://www.pbs.org/video/the-tenth-inning-the-tenth-inning-interview-extras-rotisserie/ |website=pbs.org |accessdate=2017-12-24}}</ref> During the nine-part series, a red-sweater-wearing Okrent delivered a detailed analysis of the cultural aspects of the national pastime, including a comparison of the dramatic Game 6 of the [[1975 World Series]] between the [[Boston Red Sox]] and [[Cincinnati Reds]] to the conflict and character development in [[Russian literature|Russian novels]].\n\n==The Death of Print==\nIn the late 1990s, as editor of new media at [[Time Inc.]], Okrent wrote about the future of magazine publishing.<ref name=\"Lieb\">{{cite journal |last=Lieb |first=Thom |date=March 2001 |title=Q. & A.: Breaking News |journal=The Journal of Electronic Publishing |volume=6 |issue=3 |url=http://quod.lib.umich.edu/j/jep/3336451.0006.306?view=text;rgn=main |doi=10.3998/3336451.0006.306 |accessdate=2016-04-25}}</ref> He believed that the advancement of digital technologies would make it easier for people to read newspapers, magazines and books online.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Nayar|first1=Pramod K.|title=Virtual worlds: culture and politics in the age of cybertechnology|date=2004|publisher=[[Sage Publications]]|location=New Delhi|isbn=9780761932284|page=[//books.google.com/books?id=ksmGAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA117 117]}}</ref> In late 1999, Okrent made a prediction about the future of print media in the Hearst New Media Lecture at the [[Columbia University Graduate School of Journalism|Graduate School of Journalism of Columbia University]].<ref name=\"Lieb\"/> He told his audience: {{Quote|I believe they, and all forms of print, are dead. Finished. Over. Perhaps not in my professional lifetime, but certainly in that of the youngest people in this room. Remove the question mark from the title of this talk. The Death of Print, full stop.<ref>{{cite web |last=Okrent |first=Dan |date=February 2000 |title=The Death of Print? |url=http://digitaljournalist.org/issue0002/okrent.htm |website=digitaljournalist.org |accessdate=2016-04-25}}</ref>}}\n\n==Personal life==\nOkrent has participated in [[LearnedLeague]] under the name \"OkrentD\".<ref>{{cite web |title=LL Profile: OkrentD |url=http://learnedleague.com/profiles.php?okrentd |publisher=[[LearnedLeague]] |accessdate=2014-10-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Kushner |first=Adam B. |date=August 20, 2014 |title=The coolest, weirdest Internet community you'll never be able to join |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/the-coolest-weirdest-internet-community-youll-never-be-able-to-join/2014/08/20/3c3f565e-26eb-11e4-958c-268a320a60ce_story.html |website=washingtonpost.com |publisher=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=2017-12-24}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''The Ultimate Baseball Book'' (co-editor, with Harris Lewine) (1979)\n* ''Nine Innings: The Anatomy of Baseball as Seen Through the Playing of a Single Game'' (1985)\n* ''Baseball Anecdotes'' (co-author, with Steve Wulf) (1987)\n* ''The Way We Were: New England Then, New England Now'' (1988)\n* ''[[Great Fortune: The Epic of Rockefeller Center]]'' (2003)\n* ''Public Editor #1'' (2006)\n* ''Last Call: The Rise and Fall of Prohibition'' (2010)\n* ''The Guarded Gate: Bigotry, Eugenics, and the Law That Kept Two Generations of Jews, Italians, and Other European Immigrants Out of America'' (2019)\n\n==Filmography==\n* ''[[Baseball (documentary)|Baseball]]'' (1994), (2010) | Documentary | Directed by: [[Ken Burns]]\n* ''[[Sweet And Lowdown]]'' (1999) | Role of: A.J. Pickman | Comedy-Drama | Directed by: [[Woody Allen]]\n* ''[[Wordplay (film)|Wordplay]]'' (2006) | Documentary | Directed by: [[Patrick Creadon]]\n* ''[[The Hoax]]'' (2007) | Role of: Real Publisher #1 | Comedy-Drama | Directed by: [[Lasse Hallstr\u00f6m]]\n* ''[[Silly Little Game]]'' (2010) | Documentary | Directed by: Lucas Jansen and Adam Kurland\n* ''[[Prohibition (miniseries)|Prohibition]]'' (2011) | Documentary | Directed by: [[Ken Burns]]\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Biography|Baseball|Journalism}}\n* [[List of people from Detroit]]\n* [[List of people from New York City]]\n* [[List of University of Michigan alumni]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|nm0645711}}\n* {{iobdb name|41415}}\n* {{cite web |last=Roberts |first=Russ |title=Okrent on Prohibition and His Book, ''Last Call'' |url=http://www.econtalk.org/archives/_featuring/daniel_okrent/ |work=[[EconTalk]] |publisher=[[Library of Economics and Liberty]] |authorlink=Russ Roberts |date=June 7, 2010}}\n*{{C-SPAN|Daniel Okrent}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-media}}\n{{S-new}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Public Editor]] for ''[[The New York Times]]''|years=2003\u20132005}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Byron Calame]]}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Okrent, Daniel}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:American book editors]]\n[[Ca