{"title_page": "Khoka 420", "text_new": "{{Use Indian English|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}\n{{More citations needed|date=June 2012}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Khoka 420\n| image          = Khoka 420 movie.jpg\n| caption        = Khoka 420 Theatrical poster\n| director       = [[Rajiv Kumar Biswas]]\n| producer       = [[Ashok Dhanuka]]<br /> [[Eskay Movies]]\n| writer         = Subhadip Das\n| story          = Pele\n| based on       = [[Brindavanam (2010 film)|Brindavanam]]\n| starring       = [[Dev (Bengali actor)|Dev]]<br />[[Subhashree Ganguly]]<br />[[Nusrat Jahan]]<br />[[Tapas Paul]]<br />[[Rajatava Dutta]]<br />[[Haradhan Bandopadhyay]]\n| music          = [[Rishi Chanda]]<br />[[Shree Pritam]]<br />[[Savvy Gupta|Savvy]]<br />Shrijit\n| cinematography = Shrisha Roy\n| editing        = Mohammad Kalam Khan, Saikat Sengupta\n| distributor    = [[Eskay Movies]] and [[Jalsha Movies Production]]\n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|2013|06|14}}\n| runtime        = 166 minutes\n| country        = [[India]]\n| language       = [[Bengali language|Bengali]]\n| gross          = {{INR}}8 [[crore]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1131222/jsp/t2/story_17707107.jsp|title=5 films that rocked the box office this year|newspaper=[[The Telegraph (Calcutta)|The Telegraph]]|accessdate=22 Dec 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Khoka 420''''' is a [[Cinema of West Bengal|Bengali]] [[romantic comedy]] film directed by Rajib Biswas. The film stars [[Dev (Bengali actor)|Dev]], [[Subhashree Ganguly]], [[Nusrat Jahan]], [[Tapas Paul]], [[Rajatava Dutta]]  and others. The film is a remake of the 2010 Telugu film [[Brindavanam (2010 film)|Brindavanam]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bengali/movie-reviews/Khoka-420/movie-review/20616778.cms|title=Khoka 420 Movie Review, Trailer, & Show timings at Times of India|website=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com|accessdate=2016-06-28}}</ref> starring [[N. T. Rama Rao Jr.]], [[Samantha Ruth Prabhu]] and [[Kajal Agarwal]]. The film was dubbed into Hindi as \"Mere Ustas 420\".\n\n== Plot ==\nIn this story Krish (played by [[Dev (Bengali actor)|Dev]]) is the hero and Bhoomi (played by [[Subhashree Ganguly]]) is the leading heroine.<ref name=\"ToI \u2013 16Jun2013 \u2013 Khoka 420 movie review\">{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articlelist/movie-review/20616778.cms|title=Khoka 420 movie review|last=Biswas|first=Jaya|date=16 June 2013|work=[[Times of India]]|publisher=[[The Times Group]]|accessdate=29 August 2013}}</ref> Krish is the son of a rich man. Krish (has  love interest in Megha ([[Nusrat Jahan]]). Megha also loves Krish a.k.a. Krishna. Their relationship goes fine until Megha meets Bhoomi ([[Subhashree Ganguly]]), a beautiful girl, and they become best friends. Bhoomi tells her best friend Megha about his rowdy and tough cousin who her family wants her to marry, but she does not want to. Megha gets worried about her friend and tells the problem to her boyfriend, Krish. Megha makes Bhoomi meet Krish and tells Krish to act as if Krish is Bhoomi's boyfriend and let Bhoomi's family know that Bhoomi is in a relationship with Krish. Krish does not agree at first but later agrees to help out Bhoomi. In the meantime, Bhoomi fall in love with Krish in reality. Krish also gets close to Bhoomi. Later, one day Krish gets to know that Megha and Bhoomi's fathers are step-brothers and they have a family rivalry between them from ages. Krish meets the two brothers' father ([[Haradhan Bandopadhyay]]) and gets to know why they have the rivalry and also gets to know that grandfather wants them to be together again. The grandfather gives the responsibility to Krish to get the two families together again and if he is successful he will get the hand in marriage of Megha or Bhoomi \u2013 whomever he is in love with. Krish falls in a big problem as he is not interested in all this family rivalry. But later he decides to get the family together. In the meantime, Megha gets the wrong idea that Krish and Bhoomi are cheating her and Krish is in love with Bhoomi and not her. Due to the untimely death of Late Shri Haradhan Bandopadhay, the climax of the movie was changed which made it different from the original story of Brindavanam where Krish marries Bhoomi as Megha explained.\n\n== Cast ==\n* [[Dev (Bengali actor)|Dev]] as Krish\n* [[Subhashree Ganguly]] as Bhoomi\n* [[Nusrat Jahan]] as Megha\n* [[Tapas Paul]] as Bhoomi's father (Brijeshwar Ganguly)\n* [[Rajatava Dutta]] as Megha's father (Mohanlal Ganguly)\n* [[Haradhan Bandopadhyay]] as The grandfather of Bhoomi and Megha\n* Partho Sarathi Chakraborty as Hari\n* [[Aritra Dutta Banik]] as Krish's companion\n* [[Shubhajit Bhowmik]] as Krish's companion\n* [[Supriyo Datta]] as Krish's fake father\n* [[Laboni Sarkar]] as Krish's mother\n* [[Biswanath Basu]] as Bhoomi and Megha's uncle\n* [[Kunal Padhi]] as Krish's father\n* Anjan Mahato as Krish's driver (Kamol Bhai)\n* [[Joy Badlani]] as Hari's father\n\n== Soundtrack ==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Khoka 420\n| type       = soundtrack\n| artist     = Rishi Chanda, [[Shree Pritam]], Savvy and Shrijit\n| cover      = \n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|df=y|2013|05|}}\n| recorded   = 2013\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Film soundtrack|Feature film soundtrack]]\n| length     = 34.50 min\n| label      = [[Eskay Movies]] -Eskay Music (Dhoom Music)\n| producer   = Ashok Dhanuka\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\nThe album is scored by [[Savvy Gupta|Savvy]].\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Singer !! Lyricist !! Composer !! Rating\n|-\n| 01. Mad I Am Mad || [[Mika Singh]], [[Saberi Bhattacharya]] || Gautam Sushmit || Savvy || 7.0\n|-\n| 02. Solid Case Kheyechhi || [[Bappi Lahiri]], [[Sushma Shrestha|Poornima Shrestha]] || Shree Pritam\n|Shree Pritam\n| 8.0\n|-\n| 03. Bin Tere Tere Bin || [[Zubeen Garg]] || Smarajit Bandyopadhy